        pages = {3035-3049},
     abstract = "{Samples of young Type Ia supernovae have shown 'early excess' emission
        in a few cases. Similar excesses are predicted by some explosion
        and progenitor scenarios and hence can provide important clues
        regarding the origin of thermonuclear supernovae. They are,
        however, only predicted to last up to the first few days
        following explosion. It is therefore unclear whether such
        scenarios are intrinsically rare or whether the relatively small
        sample size simply reflects the difficulty in obtaining
        sufficiently early detections. To that end, we perform toy
        simulations covering a range of survey depths and cadences, and
        investigate the efficiency with which young Type Ia supernovae
        are recovered. As input for our simulations, we use models that
        broadly cover the range of predicted luminosities. Based on our
        simulations, we find that in a typical 3 d cadence survey, only
